<font color="#FF0000">THE GREATEST HONOR</font><br>
<tt>Sat Oct  4  1:45:13 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Racism has been - for longer  than you or me.  I feel that one of the greatest honors ever bestowed on me was that I had the priviledge of being in the presence of a number of American citizens when they died while serving their country.  It is true that we did not pick those individuals we eventually had to accompany into combat.  Nevertheless, none of those men who died could have honored me more than by allowing me to be present at their physical demise.  What this means is that they are closer than family.  And all their various relations here now in the states are family.  Family does act up at times we know.  We gently overlook the faults of loved ones.  We try to influence them for the better if it is given to us.  But we never forget that all of their antics are paid for in red.  We know because we had the honor placing their loved ones in the body bags and carrying that dear weight to the choppers for evacuation to the rear.  When I was a child I thought (racism) as child, but when I became a man I put away childish things.  To those of you to whom it has been given we suffer racism, but we demonstrate a better way because of that special honor that was once bestowed upon us.  As we once sacrificed unto death, now let us learn to sacrifice unto life.     <br>

